    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Content curation</strong> is the process of finding, filtering, and sharing relevant third-party content with your audience — always with your perspective, commentary, or context added. It differs from aggregation (which is automated) because a human uses editorial judgment to decide what belongs and why.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Recommended mix</div>
            <div class="tms-value">60% original · 40% curated</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Content</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Best platforms</div>
            <div class="tms-value">LinkedIn · X · Newsletters</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Every publishing team runs out of original ideas. Content curation is how you keep cadence without pretending you invented every insight — you filter the internet on behalf of your audience and add the "why this matters" they cannot get from a Google Alert.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is content curation?</h2>
        <p>Content curation is the practice of discovering third-party articles, videos, studies, or posts, selecting the ones your audience should see, and sharing them with a layer of your own editorial context. The added context is the key attribute — without it, curation collapses into aggregation.</p>
        <p>What curation is <em>not</em>:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Not copying.</strong> Republishing someone else's article on your domain is scraping, not curation.</li>
          <li><strong>Not automated aggregation.</strong> A bot pulling headlines from RSS feeds is Google News, not a curator.</li>
          <li><strong>Not a substitute for original content.</strong> Curation supplements a publishing calendar; it does not replace one.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Every good curator adds one of three things: perspective, synthesis across sources, or ranking by importance.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">The 60/40 rule</div>
          <p>Most working content calendars settle around <strong>60% original · 40% curated</strong>. Enough original work to establish a voice; enough curation to keep the publishing cadence high without burning writers out.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why content curation matters</h2>
        <p>Curation solves the two hardest problems of running a publishing channel — volume and trust.</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Sustains cadence.</strong> Curated posts fill the gaps between original pieces. A team that publishes 3x/week originally becomes a team that publishes 5-7x/week when curation is added.</li>
          <li><strong>Establishes thought leadership.</strong> The act of picking what to share signals expertise. Every curated post says "this deserves your attention" — a stronger signal than "I wrote this."</li>
          <li><strong>Builds relationships.</strong> Attribution to the original creator earns backlinks, shares, and often a personal reply — every curated share is potential outreach.</li>
          <li><strong>Delivers audience value.</strong> Followers do not want to read 500 industry sources; they follow you because you already filter them.</li>
          <li><strong>Feeds original content.</strong> Reading widely to curate produces the raw material for future original posts.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How the content curation process works</h2>
        <p>A repeatable curation workflow has four steps.</p>
        <h3>1. Source discovery</h3>
        <p>Feed the input: <a href="/glossary/newsletter/">newsletters</a>, RSS via Feedly, X lists, Google Alerts, industry Substacks, competitor blogs, LinkedIn follows. Aim for 30-50 quality sources you can scan in under 20 minutes/day.</p>
        <h3>2. Filter and select</h3>
        <p>Not everything gets shared. A rule of thumb: only share content that (a) matches your audience's interests, (b) makes an argument you find important, and (c) you would recommend in a one-on-one conversation.</p>
        <h3>3. Add context</h3>
        <p>Every share needs 1-2 sentences that answer "why this matters to my audience." Vague endorsements ("Great read!") signal effort and add nothing. Sharp takes ("The 47% number here changes how I think about paid vs. organic acquisition") get saved and reshared.</p>
        <h3>4. Schedule and attribute</h3>
        <p>Slot the curated post into your <a href="/glossary/content-calendar/">content calendar</a>, credit the original creator by name and link, and — if platform allows — tag them so the algorithm surfaces the share back to them.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Types of content curation</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Format</th><th>What it looks like</th><th>Where it works</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Single-share commentary</strong></td><td>One link + 2-3 sentences of your take</td><td>LinkedIn, X</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Weekly roundup</strong></td><td>5-10 links grouped by theme with mini-summaries</td><td>Newsletter, blog</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Themed digest</strong></td><td>Deep dive into one topic pulling from multiple sources</td><td>Blog, newsletter</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Expert quote curation</strong></td><td>Pulling quotes from many creators on one topic</td><td>Blog, LinkedIn post</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Resource library</strong></td><td>Ongoing tagged database of curated links</td><td>Owned site, Notion</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Visual curation</strong></td><td>Screenshot + reaction, or moodboard</td><td>Instagram, Pinterest</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real content curation examples</h2>
        <h3>1. B2B director sharing daily on LinkedIn</h3>
        <p>A marketing director curates 3 industry articles per week on LinkedIn with 100-word commentary on each. Average reach: 5,000+ people. He publishes zero original long-form posts — the commentary is the original insight, the linked article is the receipt.</p>
        <h3>2. Local business "5 Things Worth Reading" newsletter</h3>
        <p>A regional accounting firm sends a weekly Friday email: 2 original tax tips, 3 curated links (SBA blog, ProPublica investigation, local business news). Open rate: 41%. Client referrals from the newsletter run 12x their paid-ad CPA.</p>
        <h3>3. SaaS company running a public reading list</h3>
        <p>A dev tools startup runs an "Every article we bookmarked this week" page tied to their content calendar. The page earned 40 backlinks in the first quarter — most from creators pleased to see their work included.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Content curation vs. aggregation — the critical difference</h2>
        <p>The words get used interchangeably. The practices are not the same.</p>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Content curation</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Human editorial judgment</li>
              <li>Context and perspective added</li>
              <li>Each share is a decision</li>
              <li>Attribution to original creator</li>
              <li>Example: "Here are the 5 studies I trust on GDPR"</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Content aggregation</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Automated collection (RSS, scraping)</li>
              <li>No commentary — just links</li>
              <li>Volume-first, no filtering</li>
              <li>Attribution optional (and often missing)</li>
              <li>Example: Google News, Techmeme</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for content curation</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Always attribute.</strong> Name the creator, link the source. Never crop out watermarks.</li>
          <li><strong>Curate niche, not broad.</strong> "Best CRO experiments this week" beats "Interesting marketing links."</li>
          <li><strong>Add your take up front.</strong> Lead with your commentary; the link comes second.</li>
          <li><strong>Balance the mix.</strong> 60% original / 40% curated works for most teams. Adjust based on platform.</li>
          <li><strong>Timebox discovery.</strong> 20-30 minutes per day scanning sources is enough. Everything beyond that becomes procrastination.</li>
          <li><strong>Turn curation into original content.</strong> The 12 best links you curated in a month become one authoritative roundup post on your own domain.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — curation as content strategy</div>
          <p>Curation supplements a voice; it cannot replace one. Publishers that share only curated links plateau within 6 months. Original perspective is what keeps audiences returning — curation compounds that voice; it does not substitute for it.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common content curation mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Skipping the commentary.</strong> A bare link with "Interesting!" is aggregation, not curation.</li>
          <li><strong>Curating stale content.</strong> Anything older than 30 days on X or LinkedIn loses momentum fast — check dates before sharing.</li>
          <li><strong>Sharing without reading.</strong> Sharing headlines you did not open turns you into a rumor mill.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring platform norms.</strong> Instagram punishes external links; LinkedIn rewards them.</li>
          <li><strong>Cropping out attribution.</strong> Guaranteed way to end a relationship with the original creator.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">What is the difference between content curation and content aggregation?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
